That's why I thought it'd be great
if you were there...

00:02:03.065 --> 00:02:07.796
He was the man. He was
the right-hand man of Lefty.

00:02:07.796 --> 00:02:09.909
&gt;&gt; Even though I argued against it,
you know, I...

00:02:09.909 --> 00:02:11.761
&gt;&gt; He fought and fought.
&gt;&gt; OK.

00:02:11.761 --> 00:02:14.904
[LAUGHTER]
OK. Now you need me.

00:02:14.904 --> 00:02:16.679
That's right.
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:18.796 --> 00:02:22.285
Really, what we grew up on was 
the first days of television,

00:02:22.285 --> 00:02:24.964
so it was really...
Sid Caesar.

00:02:24.964 --> 00:02:27.060
&gt;&gt; Oh, yeah.
&gt;&gt; And those skits with Imogene Coca

00:02:27.060 --> 00:02:28.639
and of course Carl Reiner.

00:02:28.639 --> 00:02:29.413
Of course.

00:02:29.413 --> 00:02:31.867
I liked Abbott and Costello, I liked you,

00:02:31.867 --> 00:02:33.820
you were great,
Jack E. Leonard.

00:02:33.820 --> 00:02:37.000
Sometimes I get a little bit
emotional about it to myself.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:40.510
'Cause I say, “All those good guys!"
You know?

00:02:40.510 --> 00:02:42.604
Obviously, you must have started
doing, like, stand-up…

00:02:42.604 --> 00:02:44.306
When you did stand-up at first,
you must have done…

00:02:44.306 --> 00:02:47.410
I did jokes, I did, you know, 
impressions.

00:02:47.410 --> 00:02:49.085
&gt;&gt; Yeah.
&gt;&gt; And then I looked down

00:02:49.085 --> 00:02:53.431
and see a guy with a suit,
and I’d say: "Sir, what's your name?”

00:02:53.431 --> 00:02:56.727
&gt;&gt; “Louie.”
&gt;&gt; “Louie, get another suit.”

00:02:56.727 --> 00:02:58.412
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:58.412 --> 00:03:01.649
“The suit, Louie. It don't make it".

00:03:01.649 --> 00:03:04.320
Well, I was aware like...
Johnny Carson...

00:03:04.320 --> 00:03:06.594
Yeah, you know. Somebody
like Sinatra would come on

00:03:06.594 --> 00:03:10.251
and suddenly you'd be... taking
him and wiping the floor with him.

00:03:10.251 --> 00:03:11.462
[LAUGHTER]
&gt;&gt; Oh, yeah.

00:03:11.462 --> 00:03:13.081
It was …
Did we hear that right?

00:03:13.081 --> 00:03:16.146
[APPLAUSE]

00:03:17.177 --> 00:03:20.407
&gt;&gt; They all recognize you, old-timer.
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:20.407 --> 00:03:22.782
Frank either loved you
or forget about it.

00:03:22.782 --> 00:03:26.490
&gt;&gt; But with you.
&gt;&gt; And, God, for some reason

00:03:26.490 --> 00:03:30.348
I could say... You know,
like he’d be eating, I'd say:

00:03:30.348 --> 00:03:34.923
"Frank, pass the olives.” And he'd say, “You know, I'm eating."

00:03:34.923 --> 00:03:35.939
I said: “What do you want
me to do?

00:03:35.939 --> 00:03:38.356
Drop my pants and
fire a rocket? What do I care?”

00:03:38.356 --> 00:03:40.498
[LAUGHTER]
He'd get away with it!

00:03:40.498 --> 00:03:46.871
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:46.871 --> 00:03:49.745
He enjoyed it!
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:49.745 --> 00:03:52.020
&gt;&gt; Are you still going to Vegas?
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:03:52.020 --> 00:03:52.693
You are? Yeah?

00:03:52.693 --> 00:03:54.399
When was the first time
you were in Vegas, though?

00:03:54.399 --> 00:03:57.049
In the early ’50, mid-‘50s.
&gt;&gt; Yeah. Those were good days.

00:03:57.049 --> 00:04:00.314
Yeah, I know. All the wiseguys
were great.

00:04:00.314 --> 00:04:03.476
&gt;&gt; I know, I know.
&gt;&gt; They treated us like,

00:04:03.476 --> 00:04:06.151
all of us as actors, with class,
you know?

00:04:06.151 --> 00:04:08.555
It was really great
to know those guys.

00:04:09.539 --> 00:04:11.131
&gt;&gt; Thank you.
&gt;&gt; You're welcome.

00:04:11.131 --> 00:04:13.354
&gt;&gt; What is this? Dead horse?
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:13.360 --> 00:04:16.500
Don, can I have...?
Just taste a piece of your thing there?

00:04:16.500 --> 00:04:19.040
&gt;&gt;This is what he does at dinner.
&gt;&gt; Just a bite. I just wanna take a bite.

00:04:19.040 --> 00:04:21.580
&gt;&gt; Yeah.
&gt;&gt; But you know, one of the reasons...

00:04:21.580 --> 00:04:24.760
One of the things we wanted
in “Casino” was 'cause you were...

00:04:24.764 --> 00:04:28.612
You kind of had the whole...
the look, the atmosphere,

00:04:28.612 --> 00:04:32.354
all the sense of Vegas
and you also knew Lefty Rosenthal,

00:04:32.354 --> 00:04:34.807
whom Bob was playing
under a different name.

00:04:34.807 --> 00:04:35.883
What the hell is the name
again?

00:04:35.883 --> 00:04:39.722
&gt;&gt; Ace, Ace Rothstein.
&gt;&gt; He was a big shot, you know.

00:04:39.722 --> 00:04:41.002
&gt;&gt; Yeah.
&gt;&gt; I would spend time

00:04:41.002 --> 00:04:43.176
with him here, in L.A...
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:04:43.176 --> 00:04:45.802
&gt;&gt;...and he couldn't come to Vegas
because he was in the black book.

00:04:45.802 --> 00:04:48.293
Yeah. Hours and hours
of talking with him, but...

00:04:48.293 --> 00:04:51.239
You were there when he actually
ran the place, Stardust, right?

00:04:51.239 --> 00:04:54.242
A lot of people ask me,
they say: "Who was tougher

00:04:54.242 --> 00:04:57.262
to deal with, Bob or Don?"
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:57.262 --> 00:05:00.024
&gt;&gt; And obviously...
&gt;&gt; It was him.

00:05:00.024 --> 00:05:02.233
Obviously it was him.
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:02.233 --> 00:05:04.700
'Cause one of the main things
is that he didn't have to speak.

00:05:04.700 --> 00:05:05.774
&gt;&gt; Yeah.
&gt;&gt; So you could imagine.

00:05:05.774 --> 00:05:07.922
You had to keep quiet
through a lot of the scenes

00:05:07.922 --> 00:05:09.843
and it was just the looks we had,
remember?

00:05:09.843 --> 00:05:14.996
&gt;&gt; Yeah. Just making a lot of faces.
&gt;&gt; That was funny that night you had the cigarette.

00:05:14.996 --> 00:05:17.453
How can I let it go on so long?

00:05:17.453 --> 00:05:20.251
&gt;&gt; I was staring at you.
&gt;&gt; Did I say something wrong?

00:05:21.412 --> 00:05:23.380
You were supposed to say:
"I should have known better.”

00:05:23.380 --> 00:05:25.275
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:25.280 --> 00:05:26.448
&gt;&gt; Remember that?
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:05:26.448 --> 00:05:28.820
For the kind of money you're making,
you need the cards?

